article.headline: Sixers lose winning streak as Webber dominates

images.name: Webber_Chris 030303 Inline
images.caption: Chris Webber went over the Sixers for 29 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists.

article.linkText: Despite age and ankle, Webber still tops for Kings
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Webber's signature hook shot is benefiting from his bad ankle -- because he can't jump as high, he's more focused on his follow-through. Webber had 29 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists and the Sacramento Kings snapped the Philadelphia 76ers' season-best nine-game winning streak with a 107-99 victory Monday night. Webber, who returned Feb. 23 after missing 10 games with a severely sprained left ankle, is feeling great despite all the teasing he's getting from his teammates since turning 30 Saturday. He's got his favorite shot back. ''I feel 25,'' Webber said with a smile. ''They say you're only as old as you feel.'' Yet trying to keep up with Allen Iverson made all of the Kings feel a little old. Iverson had 35 points, five rebounds, five steals and four assists as the Sixers lost for the first time since the All-Star break. Iverson scored six consecutive points during a late 8-0 run, including a 3-pointer with 3:34 left that pulled Philadelphia to 94-92. The Sixers took the lead briefly at 95-94, but couldn't hold it. ''I don't feel good about our loss at all,'' Iverson said. ''I don't care anything about moral victories. I'm too far along in my career to ever care about moral victories, especially if we have a chance to win a game.'' Peja Stojakovic made two key baskets late and Doug Christie scored off a steal on Eric Snow's inbound pass following a timeout. ''Those are two of the fastest guys in the NBA,'' Webber said of Iverson and Christie. ''That's like the world's strongest man stuff. That was a good little race.'' Snow, who has been doing almost everything right recently, missed two free throws at 2:10, and the Sixers were sloppy with the ball in the final minutes. Webber, one game after scoring 36 points and grabbing nine rebounds in a defeat at San Antonio, scored 23 of his points after halftime and Bobby Jackson had nine of his 18 points in the fourth quarter. During its winning streak, Philadelphia averaged 107.6 points a game and limited opponents to 95.6 points. The Sixers were shooting 47.8 percent during the streak, but shot 46.3 percent to Sacramento's 52.6. ''We gave this game away,'' coach Larry Brown said. ''Webber playing on one leg was just tremendous.'' Only two of Philadelphia's victories came against teams with winning records -- they beat New Jersey on Feb. 16 and the Utah Jazz on Friday. The Kings have won four in a row against Philadelphia and 12 of the last 13 in Arco Arena, where they have a five-game winning streak. Philadelphia last won in Sacramento on Dec. 30, 2000, 107-104 in overtime. Jim Jackson's 3-pointer for Sacramento with 9:33 left tied the game at 81, then Webber scored consecutive baskets and Bobby Jackson made a reverse layin for an 87-83 lead with 6:53 remaining. He then hit a 3 at 5:34 to make it 90-83. Keith Van Horn returned to the lineup after missing the victory Sunday at Denver because of a stomach virus and finished with 17 points and seven rebounds. Iverson scored back-to-back baskets early in the third quarter as the Sixers built their biggest lead of seven points, 64-57, but Webber had 15 points in the quarter to keep the Kings in it. Iverson's three-point play with 7.2 seconds left in the period gave Philadelphia a 77-76 lead heading into the final quarter. The Sixers missed eight of their first 10 shots, but still shot 54.5 percent in the first quarter and 44.2 percent for the half. They led 52-51 at halftime. Stojakovic scored seven points in a 9-2 run that gave the Kings a 10-point lead, 19-9, with 4:25 left in the first quarter. Then Van Horn scored five points during an 11-0 Sixers' run. The Kings are 13-0 against the Eastern Conference at home. ''We play well here,'' coach Rick Adelman said. ''Away teams just aren't used to playing here.'' Game notes
The Sixers signed veteran power forward Tyrone Hill to add depth to their frontcourt. To make room for Hill, 34, they waived guard Kenny Satterfield. The 6-foot-9, 250-pound Hill was cut by Cleveland on Feb. 27, and Brown had said he would like to have Hill, who played 2½ seasons for the 76ers from 1999-2001, rejoin the team. Hill had no points, three rebounds and four fouls in 12 minutes. ... Iverson increased his NBA-best streak of games scoring in double figures to 178. ... Kings center Scot Pollard was activated from the injured list, marking the second time this season he's returned from being hurt. He broke his right hand Jan. 28 -- his first game after missing 42 games with a stress fracture in his lower back.
